tates House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] since 1985, and a member of the [[Tea Party Caucus]]. The district includes [[Arlington, Texas|Arlington]], part of [[Fort Worth]], and several small towns and rural areas south of the [[Dallas-Fort Worth Metroplex]]. Following the 2014 primary defeat of [[Ralph Hall]], Barton became the dean of the Texas congressional delegation.\n\n==Early life, education, and early career==\nBarton was born in [[Waco, Texas|Waco]], [[Texas]], the son of Bess Wynell (n\u00e9e Buice) and Larry Linus Barton.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com/~battle/reps/barton.htm |title=Joe Barton Genealogy |publisher=Freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com |accessdate=2010-06-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010150518/http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/barton.htm |archivedate=2012-10-10 |deadurl=no}}</ref> He graduated from [[Waco High School]]. He attended [[Texas A&M University]] in [[College Station, Texas|College Station]] on a Gifford-Hill Opportunity Award scholarship<ref>{{cite web\n  | title =Proceedings\n  | publisher =Texas A&M University\n  | date =2004-04-06\n  | url =http://cheweb.tamu.edu/tiact/proceedings2004.pdf\n  | accessdate =2009-05-13 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060904114703/http://cheweb.tamu.edu/tiact/proceedings2004.pdf |archivedate = 2006-09-04}}</ref> and received a [[bachelor's degree|B.S.]] in [[industrial engineering]] in 1972. An [[Master of Science|M.Sc.]] in industrial administration from [[Purdue University]] followed in 1973. Following college, Barton entered private industry until 1981, when he became a [[White House Fellow]] and served under [[United States Secretary of Energy]] [[James Burrows Edwards|James B. Edwards]]. Later, he began consulting for [[Atlantic Richfield]] Oil and Gas Co., before being elected to the [[United States Congress]], in 1984.<ref name=HouseBio>{{cite web|url=http://joebarton.house.gov/biography1/ |title=Joe Barton Congressman \u2013 6th District of Texas |publisher=Joebarton.house.gov |date=1949-09-15 |accessdate=2010-06-19 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20100621055328/http://joebarton.house.gov/Back.aspx?Page=Biography <!-- archive to previous location, consistent with access date --> |archivedate=2010-06-21 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;1984\nBarton made his first run for elected office in 1984, when he entered the Republican primary for [[Texas's 6th congressional district]] after three-term incumbent [[Phil Gramm]] left his seat to run for the [[United States Senate]] that year. He finished first in the five-candidate field with 42%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=418501 |title=TX District 6 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 May 05, 1984 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029201033/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=418501 |archivedate=2013-10-29 |deadurl=no}}</ref> and very narrowly defeated Max Hoyt in the runoff with 50%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=418504 |title=TX District 6 \u2013 R Runoff Race \u2013 Jun 02, 1984 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029200844/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=418504 |archivedate=2013-10-29 |deadurl=no}}</ref> He then defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee and former State Representative [[Dan Kubiak]] 57%\u201343%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=50388 |title=TX District 6 Race \u2013 Nov 05, 1984 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029191010/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=50388 |archivedate=2013-10-29 |deadurl=no}}</ref> Barton was one of six freshmen Republican U.S. congressmen elected from Texas in 1984 known as the [[Texas Six Pack]].{{citation needed |dated=October 2013|date=October 2013}} \nIn 1986, Barton won re-election against Democratic candidate [[Pete Geren]], who would later be elected to Congress from a neighboring district. Barton defeated Geren 56%\u201344%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=38378 |title=TX District 6 Race \u2013 Nov 04, 1986 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030010515/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=38378 |archivedate=2013-10-30 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\n;1988\u20132010\nDuring this period, Barton won each re-election with 60% of the vote or more.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=1738 |title=Candidate \u2013 Joe L. Barton |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030012129/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=1738 |archivedate=2013-10-30 |deadurl=no}}</ref> His worst general election performance was in 2006, when he defeated Democratic candidate David Harris 60%\u201337%, a 23-point margin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=207706 |title=TX \u2013 District 06 Race \u2013 Nov 07, 2006 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140204032209/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=207706 |archivedate=2014-02-04 |deadurl=no}}</ref> The 2008 election was his second worst performance, defeating Democratic candidate Ludwig Otto by a 26-point margin, 62%\u201336%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=401674 |title=TX \u2013 District 06 Race \u2013 Nov 04, 2008 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022201631/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=401674 |archivedate=2012-10-22 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\nHe was only challenged in the primary twice in this time period: 1992 and 1994. In 1992, he defeated Mike McGinn 79 to 21 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=558402 |title=TX District 06- R Primary Race \u2013 Mar 10, 1992 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505140248/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=558402 |archivedate=2014-05-05 |deadurl=no}}</ref> In 1994, he defeated Jerry Goode 89%\u201311%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=560498 |title=TX District 06- R Primary Race \u2013 Mar 08, 1994 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505140246/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=560498 |archivedate=2014-05-05 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\n;2012\nBecause of the increasing controversy surrounding his record in office, election battles have been increasingly contentious. In 2011, a [[Political Action Committee|Super PAC]] was formed by Texas conservative groups to remove him and several other long-time incumbents from office.<ref>Slater, Wayne (2012-04-02) [http://trailblazersblog.dallasnews.com/archives/2012/04/texas-super-pac-targets-long-t.html \"Texas super PAC targets long-time GOP incumbents Joe Barton and Ralph Hall\"]. ''Dallas Morning News''. <!--accessed 2012-05-01--> <!-- http://web.archive.org/web/20120606164459/http://trailblazersblog.dallasnews.com/2012/04/texas-super-pac-targets-long-t.html --></ref>\nThe [[Democratic National Committee]] has used Barton's comments in political ads, shown nationally against all Republican candidates.<ref>Yellin, Jessica (2011-06-18) {{YouTube|9it4s893yDI|\"CNN Debuts DNC ad 'Stop Apologizing'\"}}. ''CNN''. <!--accessed 2012-05-01--></ref> Several websites have been created and dedicated to simply removing Joe Barton from office.  DefeatJoeBarton.com/ was created by Democratic challengers.  All content was later removed, although the site is still owned.<ref>{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504172046/http://www.defeatjoebarton.com |date=May 4, 2012 |title=www.defeatjoebarton.com }}</ref>\n\nBarton drew three primary challengers: Joe Chow, mayor of [[Addison, Texas|Addison]]; Itamar Gelbman, a security consultant; and Frank C. Kuchar, a Dallas businessman and former preacher. Chow is Texas' first [[Asian-American]] mayor. He called Barton \u201cthe most corrupt congressman in the State of Texas.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.chron.com/txpotomac/2012/05/rep-joe-barton-on-gop-primary-race-my-real-opponent-is-me/ |title=Rep. Joe Barton on GOP primary race: \u2018My real opponent is me\u2019 &#124; Texas on the Potomac |publisher=[[Houston Chronicle|Houston Chronicle Blogs]] |date=2012-05-17 |author=Dunham, Richard |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522072056/http://blog.chron.com/txpotomac/2012/05/rep-joe-barton-on-gop-primary-race-my-real-opponent-is-me/ |archivedate=2012-05-22 |deadurl=no}}</ref> At the end of March 2012, Barton had $1.3 million in cash on hand, compared with $28,800 for Chow, $178,000 for Gelbman, and $463 for Kuchar.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vaughn |first=Chris |url=http://www.star-telegram.com/2012/05/13/3957102/longtime-us-house-rep-joe-barton.html#storylink=cpy |title=Longtime U.S. House Rep. Joe Barton draws GOP challengers in District 6 race |publisher=Star-telegram.com |date=2012-05-13 |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120713133708/http://www.star-telegram.com/2012/05/13/3957102/longtime-us-house-rep-joe-barton.html |archivedate=2012-07-13 |deadurl=yes}}</ref>\n\n;2014\n\nIn the Republican primary on March 4, Barton won handy re-nomination to a sixteenth term in the U.S. House. He polled 32,579 (72.7 percent); his 2012 primary opponent, Frank Kuchar, trailed with 12,260 votes (27.3 percent).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/mar04_169_race3.htm|title=Republican primary election returns, March 4, 2014|publisher=enr.sos.state.tx.us|accessdate=2014-03-05 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306070205/https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/mar04_169_race3.htm |archivedate=2014-03-06 |deadurl=yes}}</ref> On November 4, Barton handedly won re-election over Democratic opponent Cozad. Barton serves as the Dean of the Texas Delegation for the 114th Congress.{{Citation needed|date = March 2015}}\n\n;2016\n\nBarton polled 55,197 votes (68.7 percent) in a three-candidate field for the Republican House nomination in the March 1 primary election. The runner-up, Steven Fowler, received 17,927 votes (22.3 percent).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://enrpages.sos.state.tx.us/public/mar01_273_state.htm?x=0&y=1414&id=664|title=Republican primary returns|date=March 1, 2016|publisher=Texas Secretary of State|accessdate=March 4, 2016}}</ref> To win his seventeenth consecutive term in the House, Barton then defeated in the November 8 general election the Democrat Ruby Faye Woolridge (born 1948) of [[Arlington, Texas|Arlington]], who had  polled 22,954 votes (69.7 percent) in her earlier three-candidate Democratic primary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://enrpages.sos.state.tx.us/public/mar01_233.htm|title=Democratic primary returns|date=March 1, 2016|publisher=Texas Secretary of State|accessdate=March 4, 2016}}</ref> Barton finished with 159,444 votes (58.3 percent) to Woolridge's 106,667 (39 percent). The remaining 7,185 votes (2.6 percent) went to the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] Darrel Smith, Jr.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist319_state.htm|title=Election Results|date=November 8, 2016|publisher=Texas Secretary of State|accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nBarton voted against the [[Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008]] in both of its manifestations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2008/roll671.xml |title=Final Vote Results for Roll Call 671 |publisher=Clerk.house.gov |accessdate=2013-10-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2008/roll681.xml |title=Final Vote Results for Roll Call 681 |publisher=Clerk.house.gov |accessdate=2013-10-26}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2011, Barton sponsored the [[U.S. Lighting Energy Policy#Better Use of Light Bulbs Act|Better Use of Light Bulbs Act]], which would repeal the [[Energy Independence and Security Act of 2007]], signed by President [[George W. Bush]]. The 2007 law would set energy efficiency standards for light bulbs, effectively eliminating most or all [[incandescent light bulb]]s. Barton said \"People don't want Congress dictating what [[light fixture]]s they can use.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Caygle, Heather |url=http://www.chron.com/news/nation-world/article/Republicans-demand-bulb-law-repeal-1619397.php |title=Republicans demand bulb law repeal |work=[[Houston Chronicle|Houston Chronicle Online]] |location=Washington Bureau |date=2011-03-31 |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226041645/http://www.chron.com/news/nation-world/article/Republicans-demand-bulb-law-repeal-1619397.php |archivedate=2014-02-26 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\n;Congressional Action\n* Former Chairman of the House Energy and Commerce Committee,<ref name=\"paidwife\">{{cite web  | title= Report says Barton's campaign paid wife |date=2007-06-19|accessdate= 2007-06-20|work=Fort Worth Star-Telegram <!--  removed convenience link http://www.star-telegram.com/national_news/story/141802.html, may be available to buy here http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_multi=ST|&p_text_advanced-0=%28barton%20%22paid%20wife%22%29 -->}}</ref><ref name=\"bbcwarming\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/4693855.stm | title= Politics plays climate 'hockey' |accessdate= 2007-06-20|author=Pease, Roland |publisher=BBC | date=2005-07-18 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307214120/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/4693855.stm |archivedate=2008-03-07 |deadurl=no}}</ref> primary House author of the [[Energy Policy Act of 2005]], and chairman of the House-Senate energy conference committee.{{Citation needed|date=June 2007}}\n* Both initiated and eliminated \"safe harbor\" provision for [[MTBE]] (in Energy Policy Act of 2005).<ref name=\"MSNBCNews\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2005/POLITICS/04/21/energy.bill.mtbe.ap/ |title=House approves energy bill |date=2005-04-21 |work=CNN |agency=Associated Press |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050424041210/http://www.cnn.com/2005/POLITICS/04/21/energy.bill.mtbe.ap/index.html |archivedate=2005-04-24 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n* Co-founded the Congressional Privacy Caucus, cosponsor of the anti-spyware [[Cyber-security regulation#Proposed regulation|SPY ACT]], initiated [[s:National Institutes of Health Reform Act of 2006|National Institutes of Health Reform Act of 2006]].\n* Opposed the extension of the [[Voting Rights Act]] in 2006\n* Barton has been the lead representative in forcing the switch from analog to digital TV and auctioning off the public airwaves to private companies.{{Citation needed|date = March 2015}}\n\n====Global warming controversy====\nIn 2005, prompted by a February 2005 ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' article,<ref>{{cite news|author=Regalado, Antonio  |url=http://online.wsj.com/public/article/SB110834031507653590-DUadAZBzxH0SiuYH3tOdgUmKXPo_20060207.html?mod=blogs |title=In Climate Debate, The 'Hockey Stick' Leads to a Face-Off |publisher=[[Wall Street Journal]] |date=2005-02-14 |accessdate=2010-06-19}}</ref> Barton launched an investigation into two [[climate change]] studies from 1998 and 1999.<ref name=\"bbcwarming\"/> In his letters to the authors of the studies he requested details on the studies and the sources of the authors grant funding.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2005/07/31/tree-ring-circus/ | title= Tree Ring Circus|accessdate= 2007-06-20|author= Milloy, Steven|publisher= Fox News | date=2005-07-31 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002070434/http://www.foxnews.com/story/2005/07/31/tree-ring-circus/ |archivedate=2013-10-02 |deadurl=no}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' condemned Barton's investigation as a \"[[witch-hunt]]\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/07/22/AR2005072201658.html | title= Hunting Witches|accessdate= 2007-06-20|author= Editorial|work= Washington Post | date=2005-07-23}}</ref> During Former [[Vice President]] [[Al Gore]]'s testimony to the [[Energy and Commerce Committee]] in March 2007, Barton asserted to Gore that \"You're not just off a little, you're totally wrong\" (climate scientists have refuted Barton's assertion<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.realclimate.org/index.php/archives/2007/04/the-lag-between-temp-and-co2/\n|title=The lag between temperature and CO2. (Gore\u2019s got it right.)\n|date=2007-04-27 |accessdate=2014-06-18}}</ref>), stating that \"[[Global Warming]] science is uneven and evolving.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/03/21/AR2007032100945.html |author=Pickler, Nedra |title=Gore Implores Congress to Save Planet |work= Washington Post |date=2007-03-21 |accessdate=2014-05-06 <!-- http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1Y1-104482212.html   http://web.archive.org/web/20100820092605/http://www.breitbart.com/article.php?id=D8O0O1I00&show_article=1 -->}}</ref> In 2013, when discussing the Keystone XL pipeline, he referred to the [[Genesis flood narrative]] in the Bible to argue that current climate change isn't man-made.<ref name=huffington_post_10_apr_2013>{{cite news|last=Klene|first=Chelsea|title=Joe Barton Cites Great Flood To Disprove Human Role In Climate Change|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/04/10/joe-barton-great-flood_n_3055909.html|accessdate=2013-04-13|newspaper=[[Huffington Post]]|date=2013-04-10 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130414024511/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/04/10/joe-barton-great-flood_n_3055909.html |archivedate=2013-04-14 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\n====Autism bills controversy====\nBarton tried to block the bipartisan [[Combating Autism Act|Combating Autism Act of 2006]]. He said that the money steered toward environmental causes of [[autism]] was not the reason he blocked passage of the bill.<ref>{{cite news |date=2006-10-28 |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/dn/latestnews/stories/DN-barton_28nat.ART.North.Edition1.3e00d4c.html |title=Activists Putting Heat on Barton |work=Dallas Morning News |author1=Reddy, Sudeep |author2=Loftis, Randy Lee|accessdate=2009-12-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101020043618/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/dn/latestnews/stories/DN-barton_28nat.ART.North.Edition1.3e00d4c.html |archivedate=2010-10-20 |deadurl=yes}}</ref>\n\nThe controversy stemmed from the conflict between two bills in the House and Senate.  Barton introduced the National Institutes of Health Reform Act of 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://olpa.od.nih.gov/legislation/109/publiclaws/reformact06.asp |title=National Institutes of Health Reform Act of 2006 |publisher=[[Office of Legislative Policy and Analysis]]|date= |accessdate=2013-10-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130501004808/http://olpa.od.nih.gov/legislation/109/publiclaws/reformact06.asp |archivedate=2013-05-01 |deadurl=no}}</ref> while Senator [[Rick Santorum]] introduced the Autism bill.  Santorum said in a CNN interview that the Senate bill was intended to be \"fit into\" Barton's bill in the House bill. He stated that \"I was in constant conversation with him [Barton] and many House members all last week in an attempt to help the NIH bill come through the Senate, as well as try to move the Combating Autism bill through the Senate.\"  Santorum stated that the Senate bill would investigate possible environmental causes, while the House bill would prevent that.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cLdXcb5Pc6Q&feature=watch_response |title=CNN Combating Autism Act Joe Barton |publisher=YouTube |date=2006-10-05 |accessdate=2013-10-26}}</ref>\n\nBarton let the bill die in committee, which upset many people who were vocal about saying Barton had sacrificed the interests of autistic children in the interests of the oil and gas companies that donate heavily to his campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aa2-bFlASpo&feature=related |title=Joe Barton Autism Parent Meeting \u2013 TURNED AWAY BY POLICE!|publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2013-10-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00005656 |title=Joe Barton: Campaign Finance/Money \u2013 Summary \u2013 Representative 2014 |publisher=OpenSecrets |date= |accessdate=2013-10-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029195541/http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00005656 |archivedate=2013-10-29 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\n====BP oil spill controversy====\nOn June 17, 2010, Barton accused the White House of a \"$20 billion [[Extortion|shakedown]]\" of oil giant [[BP]] after the company reached an agreement with the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] to establish an [[escrow]] account to pay the claims of people harmed by the [[BP oil spill|oil spill]] in the [[Gulf of Mexico]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vvKZh3EY9S4&feature=player_embedded |title=Barton- 'I Apologize' To BP For Escrow Fund |publisher=YouTube |date=2010-06-17 |accessdate=2010-06-19}}</ref> He made the accusation at the outset of a House hearing where BP's chief executive officer, [[Tony Hayward]], appeared for the first time before Congress.  Facing Hayward at the witness table, Barton said, \"I apologize. I do not want to live in a country where any time a citizen or a corporation does something that is legitimately wrong, is subject to some sort of political pressure that is, again, in my words \u2014 amounts to a shakedown, so I apologize.\" <ref name=\"barton-bp-apology-cbs\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/rep-joe-barton-apologizes-to-bps-tony-hayward-for-white-house-shakedown-video/ |title=Rep. Joe Barton Apologizes to BP's Tony Hayward for White House \"Shakedown\" |author=Montopoli, Brian |date=2010-06-17 |accessdate=2010-06-18|publisher= CBS News |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131204145144/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/rep-joe-barton-apologizes-to-bps-tony-hayward-for-white-house-shakedown-video/|archivedate=2013-12-04 |deadurl=no}}</ref> Prior to the establishment of the agreement, the Obama administration had been public in their criticism of BP for the oil spill; Barton and other critics{{Who|date=March 2015}} accused the White House of attempting to deflect criticism on how they handled the situation, which made it more difficult for BP to raise short-term funds in the capital market for their operations.<ref name=\"barton-bp-apology-cbs\"/>\n\nBarton's remarks were widely criticized by White House spokesman [[Robert Gibbs]], Vice President [[Joe Biden]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2010/06/17/us-oil-spill-apology-idUSTRE65G42D20100617 |title=Apology to BP's Hayward triggers uproar |publisher=Reuters |author=Holland, Steve |date=2010-06-17 |accessdate=2013-10-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130216170009/http://www.reuters.com/article/2010/06/17/us-oil-spill-apology-idUSTRE65G42D20100617 |archivedate=2013-02-16 |deadurl=no}}</ref> GOP congressional leadership<ref>{{cite news|title=GOP rushes to clean up Joe Barton mess |author=Allen, Jonathan |author2=Sherman, Jake |publisher=[[The Politico]] |date=2010-06-17 |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0610/38700.html |archivedate=May 6, 2014 |deadurl=unfit |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6PNQk3mHj }}</ref> and fellow Republicans, some of whom called on Barton to relinquish his leadership role in the [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Energy and Power|House Energy Subcomittee]].<ref>Collette, Christopher (2010-06-18) [http://www.wtsp.com/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=134419 \"Florida Congressmen denounce Joe Barton's apology to BP\"]. [[Associated Press]] via [[WTSP]].<!-- https://web.archive.org/web/20140506213703/http://archive.wtsp.com/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=134419 --></ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Jo Bonner piles on Joe Barton |author=Allen, Jonathan |publisher=[[The Politico]] |date=2010-06-18|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0610/38736.html |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6PNRPdKXn |archivedate=2014-05-06 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\nBarton later said that his earlier remarks had been \"misconstrued\" and that he believed BP was responsible for the accident.  Later that day, he issued a statement apologizing for using the term \"shakedown\" and fully retracted his apology to BP.<ref name=\"MSNBCNews\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/7574562/ns/politics/t/house-approves-billion-energy-package |title=House approves $12 billion energy bill |publisher=NBCNews.com |date=2005-04-21 |accessdate=2010-06-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506214954/http://www.nbcnews.com/id/7574562/ns/politics/t/house-approves-billion-energy-package |archivedate=2014-05-06 |deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/rep-joe-barton-retracts-apology-to-bps-tony-hayward/|title=Rep. Joe Barton Retracts Apology to BP's Tony Hayward |author=Montopoli, Brian |date=2010-06-17 |accessdate=2014-05-06|publisher= CBS News |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506210451/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/rep-joe-barton-retracts-apology-to-bps-tony-hayward/ |archivedate=2014-05-06 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\n====Position on wind energy====\n\nAt a 2009 hearing on [[renewable energy]], Barton asserted that large-scale [[wind power]] projects could slow down God's method for cooling the earth and possibly contribute to [[global warming]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sheppard|first1=Kate|title=House Republicans bring strange theories and wacky witnesses to climate hearings|url=http://grist.org/article/2009-04-20-house-republicans-bring/|website=Grist|accessdate=21 February 2016|language=English|date=20 Apr 2009|quote=''Wind is God\u2019s way of balancing heat. Wind is the way you shift heat from areas where it\u2019s hotter to areas where it\u2019s cooler. That\u2019s what wind is. Wouldn\u2019t it be ironic if in the interest of global warming we mandated massive switches to energy, which is a finite resource, which slows the winds down, which causes the temperature to go up?''}}</ref>\n\nBarton has questioned the wisdom of [[deficit spending]] to fund an extensive national [[wind turbine]] energy generation grid.<ref>{{cite web|author=Stone, Daniel |url=http://www.newsweek.com/who-joe-barton-214400 |title=Who Is Joe Barton? |publisher=Newsweek.com |date=2010-06-17 |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110119143224/http://www.newsweek.com/blogs/the-gaggle/2010/06/18/who-is-joe-barton.html |archivedate=2011-01-19 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\n====Position on Keystone pipeline====\nIn November 2011, Barton criticized President [[Barack Obama]] for delaying his decision on the [[Keystone pipeline]]. He said \"We asked him to make a decision, not to wait another two years. That's bullshit.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1111/68342.html |title=Joe Barton on Barack Obama's Keystone XL oil pipeline delay: 'That\u2019s bullsh-' |author=Buford, Talia |publisher=Politico.Com |date=2011-11-14 |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6POyK0Vtv |archivedate=2014-05-07 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\n====2011 CREW report====\nThe organization [[Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington]] (CREW) put Congressman Barton on its CREW's Most Corrupt Report 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crewsmostcorrupt.org/mostcorrupt/entry/joe-barton |title=Joe Barton (R-TX) &#124; CREW's Most Corrupt Members of Congress |publisher=Crewsmostcorrupt.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029190726/http://www.crewsmostcorrupt.org/mostcorrupt/entry/joe-barton |archivedate=2013-10-29 |deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crewsmostcorrupt.org/mostcorrupt/entry/most-corrupt-report-2011 |title=CREW\u2019s Most Corrupt Report 2011 &#124; CREW's Most Corrupt Members of Congress |publisher=Crewsmostcorrupt.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029193151/http://www.crewsmostcorrupt.org/mostcorrupt/entry/most-corrupt-report-2011 |archivedate=2013-10-29 |deadurl=no}}</ref> The article states that on Barton's 2008 financial disclosure statement, he inaccurately reported on the source of a natural gas interest that he bought into.  The share was purchased through a longtime donor and supporter who later died. This was discovered by the ''[[Dallas Morning News]]'' in 2010.<ref name=\"dallasnews1\">Michaels, Dave (2010-02-03) [http://www.dallasnews.com/news/washington/20100203-U-S-Rep-Joe-6388.ece \"U.S. Rep. Joe Barton's gas well stake raises ethical questions\"]. ''Dallas Morning News''. <!--accessed 2012-04-30--><!-- https://web.archive.org/web/20120412091049/http://www.dallasnews.com/news/washington/20100203-U-S-Rep-Joe-6388.ece --></ref> According to the ''Dallas Morning News'' article, Barton made over $100,000 on the investment.  The article and CREW Report both point out how Barton buying this undervalued asset from an \"advisor\" on energy issues could be a conflict of interest to the Congressman's position as the Chair of the House's Energy Subcommittee.  It quotes James Thurber, a professor of government at American University, as saying \"If you are elected as a public servant to try to do what is right for the public generally and then you use that position to help bring in material wealth, I think it's unethical.\"<ref name=\"dallasnews1\"/> Despite this discovery, Barton chose to neither respond to, nor correct his misreporting.{{Citation needed|date = March 2015}}\n\nCREW also reported that Barton paid his wife Terri $57,759 in salary and bonuses, from his campaign funds in the 2006 election cycle.<ref name=\"ethicsreport\">{{cite web |url=http://www.citizensforethics.org/page/-/PDFs/Reports/Family%20Affair%20%28House%29%20-%20Full%20Report.pdf?nocdn=1 | title= Family Affair \u2013 Full Report|accessdate= 2014-05-06|publisher= Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506224317/http://www.citizensforethics.org/page/-/PDFs/Reports/Family%20Affair%20%28House%29%20-%20Full%20Report.pdf?nocdn=1 |archivedate=2014-05-06 |deadurl=no}}</ref> A spokesman said that Terri served as the campaign's outreach director and planned fund raising and special events.<ref name=\"paidwife\"/> Barton's daughter Kristin was paid $12,622 in salary and bonuses and his mother, Nell Barton, was paid $7,000 for a car.<ref name=\"paidwife\"/>\n\n====Position on crude oil ban====\nBarton expressed in September 2014, his full support of the United States lifting the 40-year-old ban on crude oil exports \u2013 an issue that sparked controversy among members of the Republican Party. Several research reports have found that exporting the glut of shale oil would ultimately lower U.S. and global fuel prices, rather than raise them, U.S. public opinion remains divided on the issue.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Volcovici|first1=Valerie|title=Texas lawmaker Barton backs lifting oil export ban despite peers' misgivings|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/09/01/us-oil-exports-usa-lawmaker-idUSKBN0GW31R20140901|website=Reuters|accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Position on online poker====\nBarton has expressed his desire for pro-poker legislation to come into effect on a federal level and is hoping to introduce a new bill on the subject in April/May 2015. This bill would introduce a federal-level regulatory framework that would allow for online poker to be offered in all states.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cardschat.com/news/joe-barton-of-texas-federal-online-poker-bill-10712|title=US Representative Joe Barton of Texas Pushes In Federal Poker Bill|work=Cardschat|accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* [[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Committee on Energy and Commerce]] (Chair ''emeritus'')\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Commerce, Manufacturing and Trade|Subcommittee on Commerce, Manufacturing and Trade]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Communications and Technology|Subcommittee on Communications and Technology]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Energy and Power|Subcommittee on Energy and Power]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Environment and Economy|Subcommittee on Environment and Economy]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Health|Subcommittee on Health]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[Congressional Caucus on Turkey and Turkish Americans]]\n* Congressional Privacy Caucus (Founder/Co-Chair)\n* [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus|International Conservation Caucus]]\n* [[Republican Study Committee]]\n* Sportsmen's Caucus\n* [[Tea Party Caucus]]\n* Congressional Cement Caucus\n\n==1993 U.S. Senate election==\n{{See also|United States Senate special election in Texas, 1993}}\nIn 1993, Barton ran in the special election for the U.S. Senate seat vacated by the resignation of [[Lloyd Bentsen]], who became [[United States Secretary of the Treasury]] in the [[Clinton administration]]. Barton finished third in the contest, behind state treasurer [[Kay Bailey Hutchison]] and Senator [[Bob Krueger]], thus missing a runoff slot. He divided the more conservative vote in that election with House colleague [[Jack Fields]] of [[Houston, Texas|Houston]].\n\n==Barton Family Foundation==\nThe [[Barton Family Foundation]] was established in 2005 to support charities within the congressman's district.  His daughter-in-law, [[Amy Barton]], is the Foundation's Executive Director.  Major energy corporations, such as the [[Chicago]]-based [[Nuclear power|nuclear energy]] producer, [[Exelon]] Corporation, make major gifts to the Foundation. In June 2008, at a time when Barton had introduced legislation to assist corporations with the recycling of spent nuclear fuel, the corporation donated $25,000 to the Foundation. Exelon has also donated $80,000 to Barton's campaign funds. The Foundation gave $90,000 to the local [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Boys and Girls Club]], this is the only recorded donation made by the Foundation in its seven-year history.<ref name=Sepee>{{cite news |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/apr/06/congressmans-foundation-not-so-charitable/?page=all |title=Congressman's foundation not so charitable; Barton's group gives less than 25% to public causes|first=Jerry |last=Seper|work=Washington Times |date=2009-04-06 |page=A.1 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506222434/http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/apr/06/congressmans-foundation-not-so-charitable/?page=all |archivedate=2014-05-06 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTerri Barton divorced Joe Barton in February 2015.{{Citation needed|date = March 2015}} He has four children and five grandchildren.<ref name=HouseBio/>\n\nBarton's office announced that on December 15, 2005 he suffered a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] and was taken to [[George Washington University Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/93334-Barton_Has_Heart_Attack.php |title=Barton Has Heart Attack |author=Eggerton, John  |publisher=Broadcastingcable.com |date=2005-12-16 |accessdate=2010-06-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506222156/http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/news-articles/barton-has-heart-attack/71135 |archivedate=2014-05-06 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\nBarton revealed during a congressional hearing on video games that he was a video game player. He announced that he had \"worked [his] way up to [[Civilization IV]]\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Weigel, David |url=http://www.reason.com/hitandrun/2006/06/rep_joe_barton.shtml |title=Hit & Run Blog > Rep. Joe Barton (R-Civ IV) |publisher=Reason Magazine |date=2006-06-15 |accessdate=2010-06-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061025013833/http://www.reason.com/hitandrun/2006/06/rep_joe_barton.shtml |archivedate=October 25, 2006 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\nBarton has been an advocate of a playoff system to determine a national champion for college football, even introducing legislation to require that any game being marketed as a national championship game be a part of a playoff.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=3760232 |title=Bill would force college football playoff |publisher=[[ESPN]] |agency=Associated Press |date=2008-12-10 |accessdate=2010-06-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211153217/http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=3760232 |archivedate=2008-12-11 |deadurl=no}}</ref> On May 1, 2010, Barton grilled [[Bowl Championship Series]] coordinator [[John Swofford]], saying of the BCS that, \"It's like [[communism]]. You can't fix it.\" He also suggested that the 'C' be dropped from the BCS and it be called \"the 'BS' system.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=4121294 |title=House committee quizzes Swofford|publisher=[[ESPN]] |agency=Associated Press |date=2009-05-01 |accessdate=2010-06-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504094806/http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=4121294 |archivedate=2009-05-04 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{s-start}}\n|+ {{ushr|Texas|6|}}: Results 1984\u20132014<ref name=\"clerk\">{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/index.html |title=Office of the House Clerk \u2013 Electoral Statistics |publisher=Clerk of the United States House of Representatives |accessdate= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070725184700/http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/index.html |archivedate=July 25, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"fedelect\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fec.gov/pubrec/electionresults.shtml|title=Election Results|publisher=[[Federal Election Commission]] |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist.exe |title=1992 \u2013 Current ELECTION HISTORY |publisher=[[Secretary of State of Texas]] |accessdate=2013-10-26 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109062336/http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist.exe |archivedate=January 9, 2014 }}</ref>\n! Year\n!\n! Republican\n! Votes\n! %\n!\n! Democratic\n! Votes\n! %\n!\n! Third Party\n! Party\n! Votes\n! %\n!\n! Third Party\n! Party\n! Votes\n! %\n!\n! Third Party\n! Party\n! Votes\n! %\n!\n|-\n|[[United States House election, 1984|1984]]\n||\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |'''Joe Barton'''\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |131,482\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |57%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |[[Dan Kubiak]]\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |100,799\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |43%\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[United States House election, 1986|1986]]\n||\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |'''Joe Barton'''\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |86,190\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |56%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |[[Pete Geren]]\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |68,270\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |44%\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[United States House election, 1988|1988]]\n||\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |'''Joe Barton'''\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |164,692\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |68%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |Pat Kendrick\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |78,786\n|{{par